Title: THE FOUR OLDS
Credit: sc03 THE BARN NET + sc06 THE SEIZURE — comedy calibration
Draft date: 2026-07-12 10:29

INT. DAWES BARN - NIGHT

A pull-cord CLICKS and a work light comes up over the APOLLO PROCEDURES TRAINER.

Hand-machined gauges sit in a plywood panel, every needle painted white at the zero mark.

A crew couch rides in a welded steel cradle, bolted to the barn floor.

The triangular window looks out on nothing but a Moon painted on the barn wall, gray and cratered and eight feet across.

Along the back wall the spiral notebooks climb floor to roof, every spine dated in the same block hand, the bottom shelf starting in 1972.

CRICKET lowers himself into the couch, seventy-nine, coveralls, reading glasses pushed up on his forehead.

He sets a stopwatch on the panel ledge and squares a clipboard on his knee.

A radio speaker on the shelf hisses, then a voice comes through it.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Net's open. Tuesday, nineteen-oh-two local.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Apollo Eighteen. Lunar descent rehearsal. Number two thousand, eight hundred and six.

Cricket clicks the transmit key twice and lets it go.

CRICKET:
Copy. Panel's up.

STITCH (RADIO):
Copy, copy. You hear about Roy Alderson's place, they had the auction Saturday.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Stand by on the auction. I show us thirty seconds to ignition.

STITCH (RADIO):
They had a crowd out there, Dutch, I'm telling you, three hundred people easy on that lawn.

DUTCH (RADIO):
There were not three hundred people at Roy Alderson's.

STITCH (RADIO):
Well it was a lot.

CRICKET:
Twenty seconds.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Everybody clean it up. We're descending.

STITCH (RADIO):
So they get the tractor out front, the good green one, and a fella from over in Beatrice buys it sight unseen.

CRICKET:
Ignition. Throttle up.

Cricket's thumb walks a hand-machined lever forward and holds it.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Good ignition. Rates are nominal.

STITCH (RADIO):
Sight unseen, Gunny. Never turned it over. Man's got money to burn.

GUNNY (RADIO):
The auction is not on the net, Stitch.

STITCH (RADIO):
Everything goes on the net, Gunny. Always did.

CRICKET:
Seven thousand feet. Coming down.

DUTCH (RADIO):
I want it on the record I'm watching Bus B.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Dutch, we are aware.

DUTCH (RADIO):
It's a forty-year-old relay. I wrote it up in the binder, June of '09.

STITCH (RADIO):
Yeah, you wrote it up. We all read the binder.

CRICKET:
Five thousand.

DUTCH (RADIO):
I'm allowed to say it. It's my relay to say.

STITCH (RADIO):
So anyway the widow Alderson, she's stood there in the driveway and she says to me, Elmore, she says.

GUNNY (RADIO):
You did not talk to the widow.

STITCH (RADIO):
I talked to the widow.

CRICKET:
Three thousand feet. Rate of descent good.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Which is another thing. You missed the net that whole month, October two years back.

STITCH (RADIO):
I had my hip done.

DUTCH (RADIO):
October the fourth through the twenty-fifth. I got it logged.

STITCH (RADIO):
I had my hip done, Dutch, they cut the whole thing out and put a new one in.

GUNNY (RADIO):
The hip is not on the net either.

CRICKET:
Two thousand.

STITCH (RADIO):
Point is a man gets a new hip and the Moon waits right where it was. Fifty years of Tuesdays. It is not going to jump out at anybody.

DUTCH (RADIO):
It could. That's the whole reason for the drill.

STITCH (RADIO):
In fifty years it never once jumped out.

CRICKET:
One thousand feet.

A needle on the left panel twitches, slides half a mark toward zero, and hangs there.

CRICKET:
Got a walk on Bus B.

Dutch's voice comes back fast, then catches itself and slows.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Steady or does it stutter?

Cricket leans to the gauge, watches the needle tremble at the low edge.

CRICKET:
Stutters.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Kick it. Low left corner. Heel of your hand.

Cricket raises a boot and raps the plywood panel down in the left corner, one flat knock.

The needle jumps, climbs back up the dial, and settles white on the zero.

CRICKET:
Back up.

A long hiss on the speaker. Nobody says anything for a moment.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Well.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Don't.

DUTCH (RADIO):
June of '09.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Dutch.

STITCH (RADIO):
Aw, let him have it. He's been waiting on that a long while.

CRICKET:
Five hundred feet.

STITCH (RADIO):
So the casket, that's the part. They open it up at the front and it's veneer. The whole box. Veneer.

DUTCH (RADIO):
You cannot know it was veneer.

STITCH (RADIO):
My cousin does the finish work over there. It's veneer, I'm telling you, it's a quarter inch of walnut over the cheap stuff.

CRICKET:
Four hundred feet. Coming down nice.

The speaker goes quiet. No one calls for it. The three voices simply stop.

Cricket's thumb rides the throttle down, easy, watching the painted Moon fill the triangular window.

CRICKET:
Three hundred.

The barn is silent except for the hiss of the open channel.

A small green bulb on the panel lights.

CRICKET:
Contact light. Engine stop.

Cricket lifts his thumb off the lever and sets both hands flat on the clipboard.

One beat. The work light hums. Nobody keys a mic.

STITCH (RADIO):
You came in hot on the throttle there at the end.

CRICKET:
I did not.

GUNNY (RADIO):
The man is on the ground, Colonel.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Contact, nineteen forty-one local. I've got it down.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Net closed. Same time Tuesday.

STITCH (RADIO):
God willing.

Cricket clicks the transmit key twice.

Two clicks answer back from the speaker. Then two more. Then two more, fainter, from farther off.

The speaker cuts to dead air.

Cricket pulls a spiral notebook off the shelf and opens it flat to a fresh page.

He writes in ballpoint block letters, slow, and the words fill the top line. T+2,806. BUS B CORRECTED. CONTACT 19:41. CREW PRESENT BY RADIO.

He runs his thumb down the dated spines on his way to the door, top shelf to bottom.

He kills the work light and steps out. A padlock hangs on the hasp.

He tests it with one pull, and it holds.

Beyond the barn stands the farmhouse, and no lights are on inside it.

EXT. DAWES FARM - DAY

Two black SUVs and a county flatbed climb the gravel drive and stop short of the barn.

In the lead SUV, PELL rides shotgun, fifties, pressed shirt, a laminated badge on a lanyard, a phone propped in the dashboard mount.

A voice comes off the phone, tinny and bored.

HOLLOWAY (RADIO):
Saturday. And a real one, something that actually verifies, not some old shed you wrote up to pad your numbers. You miss it, they put your office under Lincoln's, and I got no reason left to pick up when you call.

PELL:
You'll have it.

Pell taps the phone dark, flips down the visor, and checks his hair in the little mirror. He steps out already smiling.

CRICKET stands in the open barn doorway, seventy-nine, coveralls, both boots planted on porch boards still bright with new paint.

Off by the flatbed waits WADE, mid-forties, county tan, his hat in both hands.

PELL:
Morning. Real pretty piece of ground you got up here.

Cricket says nothing. Pell keeps coming, a tablet in the crook of his arm.

PELL:
Appreciate everybody's patience this morning. Truly. We'll be light on our feet, in and gone.

Two movers in company polos wheel a dolly up the ramp and past Cricket into the barn.

PELL:
Look at that framing. They don't put a building together like this anymore.

Pell thumbs the tablet and reads down a list.

PELL:
All right. One crew couch, one panel assembly, one altitude indicator--

CRICKET:
Attitude.

Pell clicks a pen and marks the line.

PELL:
Noted.

Inside, a mover cracks his knuckle on the steel cradle and hisses through his teeth.

Cricket lifts a socket off the pegboard and holds it out. The mover takes it and can't look at him.

CRICKET:
It was surplus. Nineteen seventy-five. Told it'd be scrapped otherwise.

Pell doesn't look up from the tablet.

PELL:
Paperwork says otherwise.

He peels an orange sticker off a sheet and smooths it flat to the panel with his thumb. The sticker reads LUNAR HERITAGE NEUTRALIZATION ACCORD, EX-NASA ASSET RECOVERY.

Pell drifts to the back wall and pulls one spiral notebook down. He fans three pages of grid-ruled block printing.

PELL:
Personal papers.

He looks another second, then drops it back on the shelf crooked.

PELL:
No salvage value. Leave them.

The movers get the dolly under the trainer and take up the weight.

CRICKET:
Not one of you ever built a thing out here. Now it's all yours.

Pell stops. He sets the tablet down at his side and looks at Cricket, and the warmth goes out of his voice without any heat coming into it.

PELL:
You didn't build this either, Mr. Dawes. Nineteen seventy-five, it should've gone back to NASA and it never did, and nobody asked why for fifty years. You kept it. That's all. Long enough that theft starts to feel like inheritance.

Cricket doesn't answer that.

The dolly rolls the trainer down the ramp and out into the daylight. A clean rectangle shows on the floor where it stood, four bolt holes at the corners.

Cricket steps into the empty doorway and sets his boots.

CRICKET:
You'll have to move me, Wade.

Wade comes up the ramp, hat still in one hand.

WADE:
Earl.

He takes Cricket by both arms, gentle, and walks him a few steps to the side. Cricket lets him. Neither says anything more.

Wade keeps his voice low, close to Cricket, his back to Pell.

WADE:
Federal list came down Tuesday. County don't see a dime off it. Nobody does.

CRICKET:
Where's it go.

WADE:
Warehouse outside Lincoln, is what I hear. Same one as the rest of it.

Wade turns the hat over in his hands.

WADE:
There's a window to put in an appeal on it. It's open till four, if you want the number.

The movers slide the trainer onto the flatbed and throw a strap over it. Pell signs the tablet and tucks his pen away.

PELL:
Folks, I know change feels sudden. But like the Accord reminds us, harmony is a verb.

He gives the doorway a small nod, climbs into the SUV, and the two trucks pull off down the drive with the flatbed behind.

The dust settles over the yard. Cricket walks back in and stops at the edge of the bare rectangle.

He presses one hand hard to the back of his neck, takes one breath, and straightens.

On the workbench sits a small radio the movers left behind. Cricket thumbs it on.

CRICKET:
Net's open. Wednesday.

The speaker crackles and three voices come back over each other, fast.

STITCH (RADIO):
We're here, Earl.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Standing by.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Copy. Go ahead when you're set.

Cricket reaches up and pulls the work light on over the empty floor.
